krijk","North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England":"North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England"},"en":{"about 1329–":"about 1329–Deceased","1329–Female":"1329–Deceased","1290–1360":"1290–1360","1330–1413":"1330–1413","1345–1425":"1345–1425","–Male":"Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1425":"1425","about 1329":"about 1329","1413":"1413","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","about 1345":"about 1345","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Hemsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hemsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England":"North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Bissett","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>biset</i> ‘dark’, a diminutive of <i>bis</i> (see   Biss  ).","Altered form of French <b>Bizet</b>: nickname for someone with a dark complexion, derived from <i>bis</i> ‘grayish-brown’. Altered ending reflects the Canadian and American French practice of sounding the final <i>-t</i>. Compare   Bissette  .","History: The surname <i>Bissett</i> (see 1 above) was brought to Scotland from Nottinghamshire <i>c.</i> 1175 by Henricus Byset, an Englishman who became a retainer of King William the Lion. — It was Jean George Bizet from Haute-Saône, France, whose surname was changed to <i>Bissett</i> (see 2 above) after his immigration to NS, Canada, in 1752."],"variants":[{"name":"Biss","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>bis</i> ‘brownish or dark gray’ (Old French <i>bis</i>), denoting someone with a dark complexion or who wore dark clothing.","South German: nickname for a cutting, sarcastic person, from <i>Biss</i> ‘bite’."]},{"name":"Bissette","meanings":["American French: variant of   Bissett  ."]},{"name":"Bisset","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): variant of   Bissett  .","French: from a diminutive of Old French <i>bisse</i> ‘fine linen’ (see   Bisson  )."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Alice Bissett was born about 1329, in Hemsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom as the daughter of John Biset and Mrs. Biset. She married John Wentworth in 1355, in North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"about 1329–":"umbes 1329–Surnud","1329–Female":"1329–Surnud","1290–1360":"1290–1360","1330–1413":"1330–1413","1345–1425":"1345–1425","–Male":"Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1425":"1425","about 1329":"umbes 1329","1413":"1413","1345":"1345","1355":"1355","about 1345":"umbes 1345","1330":"1330","1360":"1360","1329":"1329","1290":"1290","Hemsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hemsworth, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"North Elmsall, West Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England":"North Elmsall, Yorkshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1329–"